bibdata.title: Please index two dissertations in staging

comments.body: On https://catalog-staging.princeton.edu/catalog/99129108711406421/ there is a 506g value set but our indexing expects that to be processed as embargo when subfield 5 in 506 is set to NjP, https://github.com/pulibrary/bibdata/blob/main/marc_to_solr/lib/embargo_date_extractor.rb#L15-L16. Feature commit. https://github.com/pulibrary/bibdata/pull/2170/files.
Can we add that value to the record with a 506 and a 506 to the other record and retry?

Sorry, just to clarify, the source record for https://catalog-staging.princeton.edu/catalog/99129104070306421 does not have an embargo at the source.  The source record for https://catalog-staging.princeton.edu/catalog/99129108711406421 does have one, however.  It looks like the "NjP" value being missing from 506 subfield 5 is what's causing the date parsing issue, is that right?

comments.body:
> Another idea is to not include properties that don't have values in the metadata json. This seems a bit simpler.

This is a good idea, but I'm not sure if it fixes the fundamental problem of the schema being able to change over time. The most common issue is new fields that upstream doesn't have, but we could also add or change a default value, serialize something different, choose to delete a field on load, etc.
